					<h2 class="comment-author">
													<a class="comment-author-link" href="http://blogs.sophos.com/2014/03/03/cryptolocker-surfaces-in-fake-uk-royal-mail-emails-many-victims-willing-to-pay/" itemprop="author">Cryptolocker surfaces in fake UK Royal Mail emails, many victims willing to pay | Sophos Blog</a>
											</h2>
					<time class="comment-meta-item" datetime="2014-03-03T05:42-05:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="#comment-331" itemprop="url">03 March 2014 at 5:42 am</a></time>
														</div>
				<div class="comment-content post-content" itemprop="text">
					<p>[&#8230;] There is no chance to break the encryption, so even removing Cryptolocker won&#8217;t get your files back. We advise that you always keep your computer protected with security software, and back up your files so you can get always them back. Also, don&#8217;t open attachments in emails from people you don&#8217;t know &#8212; the cyber crooks are especially good at tricking people through social engineering. [&#8230;]</p>
					<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://news.sophos.com/en-us/2014/01/03/spam-emails-delivering-social-engineering-attacks-how-to-protect-your-business-users/?replytocom=331#respond' data-commentid="331" data-postid="23499" data-belowelement="comment-331" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Cryptolocker surfaces in fake UK Royal Mail emails, many victims willing to pay | Sophos Blog" aria-label='Reply to Cryptolocker surfaces in fake UK Royal Mail emails, many victims willing to pay | Sophos Blog'>Reply</a>				</div>
